    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1943-05-16T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1943-05-16T00:00:00-05:00" n="27"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d27">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">Hopkins Papers</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Prime Minister <persName type="from">Churchill</persName>’s
                        Assistant Private Secretary</hi> (<persName>
                        <hi rend="italic">Rowan</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the President’s Special Assistant</hi>
                        (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Hopkins</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1943-05-16">May 16,
                            1943</date>.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Mr. Hopkins</hi>: I attach a list in duplicate of the Prime
                    Minister’s engagements. Perhaps you could kindly pass one copy on to Mrs.
                    Roosevelt. I have no doubt that additional engagements, such as meetings with
                    the Combined Chiefs of Staff, will arise.</p>
                <p>Perhaps I may mention the following points to which I referred this morning: <list>
                        <label>
                            <hi rend="italic">a</hi>.</label>
                        <item>Thursday, 20th, Admiral Brown and Tommy<note n="1" xml:id="d27fn1">The
                                reference here is presumably to Commander Thompson, the Prime
                                Minister’s Personal Assistant.</note> are arranging the concert. We
                            are fixing the meeting with Empire representatives at 5:45 in the Monroe
                            Room at the White House, which you kindly said we could use.</item>
                        <label>
                            <hi rend="italic">b</hi>.</label>
                        <item>I assume I may inform Mr. Early and Mr. Morgan, our information
                            representative, that the Prime Minister has been invited and will attend
                            Friday’s press conference.<note n="2" xml:id="d27fn2">Churchill did not,
                                in fact, attend Roosevelt’s press conference on May 21. Roosevelt
                                and Churchill did hold a joint press conference on May 25, for the
                                record of which see <hi rend="italic">post</hi>, <ref
                                    target="#pg_211">p. 211</ref>.</note>
                        </item>
                        <label>
                            <hi rend="italic">c</hi>.</label>
                        <item>Week-end. The <gloss target="#t_PM1">P.M.</gloss> feels he must stay
                            at Washington and proposes then to see the many people he should see. He
                            does not wish in any way to interfere with the President’s arrangements
                            and has accordingly asked us to arrange that he and his staff should go
                            to the Embassy for the week-end.<note n="3" xml:id="d27fn3">Churchill
                                apparently returned to the White House on the evening of May 23; see
                                the editorial note, <hi rend="italic">post</hi>, <ref
                                    target="#pg_183">p. 183</ref>.</note>
                        </item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <p>I attach a copy of the lists of people for the Prime Minister to see, suggested
                    by the President, and by yourself and Lord Halifax. As I told you, the Prime
                    Minister does not now propose to see Mr. Spangler and feels also that it is
                    rather out of his beat to see Mr. Murray and Mr. Green. You said that if he did
                    not see these two it would be inappropriate for him to see Mr. Tobin. Perhaps
                    you could mention this to the President as it was he who suggested Mr.
                    Tobin.</p>
                <p>As regards the address to Congress, I am not certain at what time it is to start,
                    as I have seen various reports.<note n="4" xml:id="d27fn4">Regarding Churchill’s
                        address to a joint session of the Houses of Congress at noon on May 19,
                        1943, see the editorial note, <hi rend="italic">post</hi>, <ref
                            target="#pg_117">p. 117</ref>.</note> Also, do you know whether it is to
                    be broadcast in U.S. and the U.K. as last time?</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>T. L. <hi rend="smallcaps">Rowan</hi>
                    </signed>
                    <lb/> 16.v.43.</closer>
                <pb facs="0124" n="22" xml:id="pg_22"/>
                <frus:attachment>
                    <opener>
                        <seg rendition="#center">[Annex 1]</seg>
                    </opener>
                    <head>
                        <hi rend="italic">List of Prime Minister Churchill’s Engagements</hi>
                    </head>
                    <p rend="center">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Engagements</hi>
                    </p>
                    <table cols="2" rows="22">
                        <row>
                            <cell rendition="#nowrap #top">
                                <hi rend="italic">Monday 17</hi>.</cell>
                            <cell>Return White House for lunch.<note n="5" xml:id="d27fn5">Roosevelt
                                    and Churchill spent the weekend of May 14–17, 1943, at Shangri
                                    La, the President’s mountain camp in Maryland; see the editorial
                                    note, <hi rend="italic">post</hi>, <ref target="#pg_86">p.
                                        86</ref>.</note>
                            </cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell rend="padding-left: 1.5em" rendition="#nowrap #top">6:00
                                p.m.</cell>
                            <cell>Lord Knollys.</cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell rendition="#nowrap #top">
                                <hi rend="italic">Tuesday 18</hi>.</cell>
                            <cell/>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell rend="padding-left: 1.5em" rendition="#nowrap #top">1:30
                                p.m.</cell>
                            <cell>Lunch Embassy, Duke of Windsor.</cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell/>
                            <cell>Afternoon and after-dinner, prepare speech.</cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell rendition="#nowrap #top">
                                <hi rend="italic">Wednesday 19</hi>.</cell>
                            <cell/>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell rend="padding-left: 1.5em" rendition="#nowrap #top">Noon ?</cell>
                            <cell>Address Congress.<note n="6" xml:id="d27fn6">See the editorial
                                    note, <hi rend="italic">post</hi>, <ref target="#pg_117">p.
                                        117</ref>.</note>
                            </cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell/>
                            <cell>Lunch at Capitol, followed by interview with Foreign Affairs
                                Committees of both Houses.<note n="7" xml:id="d27fn7">Regarding
                                        <gloss target="#t_Churchill1">Churchill</gloss>’s
                                    Congressional luncheon meeting, see the editorial note, <hi
                                        rend="italic">post</hi>, <ref target="#pg_117">p.
                                    117</ref>.</note>
                            </cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell rend="padding-left: 1.5em" rendition="#nowrap #top">5:30
                                p.m.</cell>
                            <cell>Mr. Malcolm MacDonald. (Not yet fixed)</cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell/>
                            <cell>Mr. Mackenzie King comes to White House for night.<note n="8"
                                    xml:id="d27fn8">Regarding the Roosevelt–Churchill–Mackenzie King
                                    conversation on the evening of May 19, see the editorial note,
                                        <hi rend="italic">post</hi>, <ref target="#pg_123">p.
                                        123</ref>.</note>
                            </cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell rendition="#nowrap #top">
                                <hi rend="italic">Thursday 20</hi>.</cell>
                            <cell/>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell rend="padding-left: 1.5em" rendition="#nowrap #top">Noon</cell>
                            <cell>Pacific Council.<note n="9" xml:id="d27fn9">For the record of the
                                    meeting of the Pacific War Council on May 20, 1943, see <hi
                                        rend="italic">post</hi>, <ref target="#pg_134">p.
                                    134</ref>.</note>
                            </cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell rend="padding-left: 1.5em" rendition="#nowrap #top">5:00
                                p.m.</cell>
                            <cell>Band concert at White House.</cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell rend="padding-left: 1.5em" rendition="#nowrap #top">5:45
                                p.m.</cell>
                            <cell>Empire Representatives at White House.</cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell/>
                            <cell>Dinner at Embassy with Mr. and Mrs. Hopkins and Mr. and Mrs.
                                Harriman.</cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell rendition="#nowrap #top">
                                <hi rend="italic">Friday 21</hi>.</cell>
                            <cell/>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell rend="padding-left: 1.5em" rendition="#nowrap #top">10:30
                                a.m.</cell>
                            <cell>Press Conference.<note n="10" xml:id="d27fn10">The
                                    Roosevelt–Churchill joint press conference was not held until
                                    May 25; for the record of the conference, see <hi rend="italic"
                                        >post</hi>, <ref target="#pg_211">p. 211</ref>.</note>
                            </cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell rend="padding-left: 1.5em" rendition="#nowrap #top">1:00
                                p.m.</cell>
                            <cell>Lunch with President and Mme. Chiang Kai Shek.<note n="11"
                                    xml:id="d27fn11">This luncheon appears to have been cancelled;
                                    for Churchill’s own account of the abortive arrangements for the
                                    lunch, see <hi rend="italic">Hinge of Fate</hi>, p. 797.</note>
                            </cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell/>
                            <cell>Dine at Embassy to meet U.S. Cabinet Ministers, etc.<note n="12"
                                    xml:id="d27fn12">No record has been found to indicate that
                                        <gloss target="#t_Churchill1">Churchill</gloss> dined with
                                    United States Cabinet officers on May 21; for the record of
                                    Prime Minister’s luncheon meeting with several United States
                                    officials on May 22, 1943, see <hi rend="italic">post</hi>, <ref
                                        target="#pg_167">p. 167</ref>.</note>
                            </cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell rendition="#nowrap #top">
                                <hi rend="italic">Week-end</hi>
                            </cell>
                            <cell>Stay at Embassy.</cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell rendition="#nowrap #top">
                                <hi rend="italic">Monday 24</hi>
                            </cell>
                            <cell>Return to White House.<note n="13" xml:id="d27fn13">
                                    <gloss target="#t_Churchill1">Churchill</gloss> appears to have
                                    returned to the White House on the evening of May 23; see the
                                    editorial note, <hi rend="italic">post</hi>, <ref
                                        target="#pg_183">p. 183</ref>.</note>
                            </cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell/>
                            <cell>Dine Embassy with Heads of Missions.</cell>
                        </row>
                    </table>
                </frus:attachment>
                <pb facs="0125" n="23" xml:id="pg_23"/>
                <frus:attachment>
                    <opener>
                        <seg rendition="#center">[Annex 2]</seg>
                    </opener>
                    <head>
                        <hi rend="italic">List of Persons Suggested to Prime Minister Churchill To
                            See</hi>
                        <note n="14" xml:id="d27fn14">It is not known how many of the persons herein
                            listed actually met with Churchill. Available information is set forth
                            in the succeeding footnotes.</note>
                    </head>
                    <p rend="flushleft">The President Suggests:</p>
                    <table rend="width: 90%" rendition="#center-block">
                        <row>
                            <cell cols="2">Mr. Phillips—who was in India.<note n="15"
                                    xml:id="d27fn15">Phillips, who returned from his mission to
                                    India at the beginning of May 1943, had an interview with
                                    Roosevelt on May 11 and gave the President some additional views
                                    in a letter dated May 14, 1943, <ref target="frus1943v04#pg_220">
                                        <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1943, vol. <hi
                                            rend="smallcaps">iv</hi>, p. 220</ref>. Regarding the
                                    meeting between Phillips and <gloss target="#t_Churchill1"
                                        >Churchill</gloss> on the morning of May 23, 1943, see the
                                    editorial note, <hi rend="italic">post</hi>, <ref
                                        target="#pg_177">p. 177</ref>.</note>
                            </cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell>Mr. Tobin.</cell>
                            <cell/>
                        </row>
                    </table>
                    <p rend="flushleft">The Ambassador and Mr. Hopkins Suggest:</p>
                    <table rend="width: 99%" rendition="#center-block">
                        <row>
                            <cell rendition="#hanging">The Vice President,<note n="16"
                                    xml:id="d27fn16">A participant in the American–British luncheon
                                    meeting of May 22, 1943; see <hi rend="italic">post</hi>, <ref
                                        target="#pg_166">p. 166</ref>.</note>
                            </cell>
                            <cell rendition="#hanging">Mr. Jesse Jones,</cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell rendition="#hanging">Colonel Stimson,<note n="17" xml:id="d27fn17"
                                    >Stimson participated in the American–British luncheon of May
                                    22, 1943, and met privately with <gloss target="#t_Churchill1"
                                        >Churchill</gloss> directly afterwards; see <hi
                                        rend="italic">post</hi>, <ref target="#pg_166">pp. 166</ref>
                                    and <ref target="#pg_172">172</ref>.</note>
                            </cell>
                            <cell rendition="#hanging">General Somervell</cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell rendition="#hanging">Colonel Knox,</cell>
                            <cell rendition="#hanging">Mr. Phil Muray, <gloss target="#t_CIO1"
                                    >C.I.O.</gloss>,</cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell rendition="#hanging">Mr. Morgenthau,</cell>
                            <cell rendition="#hanging">Mr. Bill Green, <gloss target="#t_AFofL1"
                                    >A.F. of L.</gloss>,</cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell rendition="#hanging">Mr. Welles,<note n="16" xml:id="d27fn18">A
                                    participant in the American–British luncheon meeting of May 22,
                                    1943; see <hi rend="italic">post</hi>, <ref target="#pg_166">p.
                                        166</ref>.</note>
                            </cell>
                            <cell rendition="#hanging">Mayor Kelly,</cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell rendition="#hanging #top">Mr. Walter Lippmann,</cell>
                            <cell rendition="#hanging">Mr. Spangler, Chairman,<lb/>Republican
                                Party,</cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell rendition="#hanging #top">Mr. Harold Ickes,<note n="16"
                                    xml:id="d27fn19">A participant in the American–British luncheon
                                    meeting of May 22, 1943; see <hi rend="italic">post</hi>, <ref
                                        target="#pg_166">p. 166</ref>.</note>
                            </cell>
                            <cell rendition="#hanging">Mr. Frank Walker, Chairman,<lb/>Democratic
                                Party and <lb/> Postmaster General.</cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell rendition="#hanging">Mr. Donald Nelson,</cell>
                            <cell/>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell rendition="#hanging">General Stilwell,<note n="18"
                                    xml:id="d27fn20">For Stilwell’s record of his meeting with
                                        <gloss target="#t_Churchill1">Churchill</gloss> on the
                                    morning of May 22, 1943, see <hi rend="italic">post</hi>, <ref
                                        target="#pg_165">p. 165</ref>.</note>
                            </cell>
                            <cell/>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell rendition="#hanging">General Chennault,<note n="19"
                                    xml:id="d27fn21">According to the account in Claire Lee
                                    Chennault, “<hi rend="italic">Way of a Fighter</hi> (New York:
                                    G. P. Putnam’s Sons, 1949), p. 227, <gloss
                                        target="#t_Churchill1">Churchill</gloss> held a private
                                    meeting with Chennault at breakfast sometime near the end of the
                                    Conference. No official record of the meeting has been
                                    found.</note>
                            </cell>
                            <cell/>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell rendition="#hanging">Admiral Land,</cell>
                            <cell/>
                        </row>
                    </table>
                </frus:attachment>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
